'''Aero Warriors''' is a nickname for four automobiles, also called '''aero-cars''', developed specifically to race on the  circuit by , ,  and  for the  and  racing seasons. The cars were based on production stock cars but had additional aerodynamic features. 
The first Aero Warrior was the 1969 . The  already had a  design; the Talladega added a longer, slightly rounded front end. The second Aero Warrior was the 1969 . The Cyclone was nearly identical to the  with the only major distinctions being the front grill and rear taillights. Another aero car is the , which had a more radical aerodynamic nose as well as a high-mounted wing at the rear. The final Aero Warrior was the   (based on the ), which had the same aerodynamic additions as the Daytona. Because of their wings, the  Aero Warriors are sometimes called the '''Winged Warriors'''. 
Due to NASCAR  rules a minimum number of these cars had to be offered for sale to the public so there are approximately 3,000 of these cars in private ownership. The Aero Warriors were successful in winning many races but NASCAR made rule changes that equalized the advantages in . Plymouth made a Superbird prototype in 1971 but it did not go into production.